We mark S&P 500 and VIX index options to current ADV levels (tracking \(+8\%\) YoY 3Q25TD) as well as other products CBOE offers including multi- listed options \((+13\%)\) , VIX futures, and cash equities. We adjust FY25 adjusted expenses in line with the new guidance of \(\) 832- 847\mathsf{mn}\$ as updated during the 2Q25 earnings report (JPMc \(\) 844\mathsf{mn}\$ ). Our rating is unchanged as our Dec 2025 price target falls to \(\) 216\$ after more tepid index options pricing assumptions.

We rate Cboe Underweight. We think the 0DTE trend- which has driven much of Cboe's SPX franchise- has seasoned and no longer is growing that business. SPX options open interest has started to decline for its core SPX options product. We also see growth in the VIX franchise decelerating- both trading volume and open interest. With higher comps, persistent competition, and a lower top- line guide from management, we are skeptical of the earnings outlook for 2025 and see the stock as having potential downside.
Our Dec 2025 price target is \(216. We arrive at our price target for Cboe by applying a 22x multiple to our revised 2026 EPS estimate.

We rate Cboe Underweight. CBOE had successfully grown its SPX franchise with the support of 0DTE contracts, but we think this catalyst has seasoned, as we now observe a stabilizing and in some places shrinking of the SPX franchise. Likewise, we see the VIX franchise decelerating as well. Finally, we think CBOE benefitted from peak earnings in 2024 given the elevated equity market volatility and greater participation of retail investors; as such, we see downside risk here and higher comps for 2025 results. Finally, we think the observed market share loss in multi- listed options will persist as new entrants erode Cboe's pricing power. With perhaps lower volatility, higher comps, and pricing pressure from new entrants, we think there are better places to put money to work in our exchange sub- sector. Underscoring this point is Cboe's valuation, which we view as being overly generous; we view Cboe being largely overvalued beyond \(20x\) with a price target of \(\) 216\$

Our Dec 2025 price target is \(\) 216\(. We arrive at our price target for Cboe by applying a\) 22x multiple to our revised 2026 EPS estimate. We increased our multiple to reflect Cboe's transition into more "steady state" business with a new CEO and a less outsized investment period. This is a discount to peers like ICE and Nasdaq, which are trading around \(25x\) FY26E Bloomberg consensus numbers.

In index options, we are skeptical that retail adoption further drives ODTE penetration given the original adopters seemed to have skewed more institutional and the commission pricing structure may be new to certain retail platforms; however, index options are launching at Robinhood, and both management teams seem enthusiastic about the opportunity. ODTE penetration has stalled in the high 40s, but if retail adopts ODTE more meaningfully than we expect, the SPX franchise could revert and grow more meaningfully than modelled.
